He was born on February 22, 1732 (or December 11, 1731 according to the Julian calendar then in use),[a] at his parents' second home (Washington Hall) in Westmoreland County, Virginia.[b][c] His father Augustine had moved the family from their ancestral home in Popes Creek in 1735,[d] when George was three years old. As a child, he suffered from smallpox which permanently scarred his face.[6][e] Washington grew up in an area where tobacco was grown by tenant farmers and plantation owners, including his father who also worked as a surveyor and justice of the peace.[10] Washington gained valuable military skills while commanding the Virginia militia during the French and Indian War. After the British defeated France in Canada in 1759 and 1760, Parliament enacted a series of measures known as the "Tax Acts" that imposed taxes on American colonies without their consent; these acts were deeply unpopular among Americans, especially Virginians.[f] In 1767, Washington married Martha Dandridge Custis, a wealthy widow whom he greatly respected. He eventually became a leader in Virginian politics and represented Virginia in the House of Burgesses, gaining the trust of many influential figures in the colony.
